</div>“SHIPYARDS are like banks,” says Jon Windham, an analyst at Barclays. As with a run on a bank, “the mere rumour of failure can prove lethal.” Shipyards rely on progress payments from customers to complete orders. But if buyers sense that a yard is heading for bankruptcy, Mr Windham argues, they will stop paying instalments—making it more likely that the ailing yard goes under. His theory may shortly be put to the test in China.The combination of excess worldwide capacity in shipbuilding and a domestic credit crunch is pushing some Chinese yards to the brink, just as the new leaders in Beijing are poised to move ahead with tough economic reforms even where these bring social costs such as job losses. That the shipbuilders are national champions in an industry deemed strategically important makes their crisis an even more serious challenge to the leaders’ resolve.All eyes are on Rongsheng, China’s biggest private-sector shipyard, which has suffered several blows. New orders have plunged this year, and the firm recently said it may post a loss for the first half. Lay-offs and overdue pay have...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:124:"http://www.economist.com/news/business/21581753-ailing-shipbuilders-test-chinas-commitment-reform-too-sick-sail?fsrc=rss|bus";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:111:"http://www.economist.com/news/business/21581753-ailing-shipbuilders-test-chinas-commitment-reform-too-sick-sail";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"Thu, 11 July 2013 14:58:10 GMT";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:40:"
      
      
      
      
      
    ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"The Dell buy-out: Hobson’s choice";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1413:"<p>WHICH would you choose: $13.65 for sure now, or a slim chance of $14 in a few months? That is the question before Dell’s shareholders in a vote on July 18th. With Silver Lake, a private-equity firm, Michael Dell is offering $13.65 a share to buy them out of the company he founded. The deal values the computer-maker at $24.4 billion. (Mr Dell is the biggest shareholder, with a 15.6% stake.) Carl Icahn, an activist investor, and Southeastern Asset Management, an investment firm, are urging rejection. They say Mr Dell and his pals want the company on the cheap.Mr Icahn and Southeastern, together holders of 12.8% of Dell’s shares, are not the only dissenters. Yet Mr Dell and Silver Lake are likely to get their way—even though Mr Dell is not voting. On July 8th they won the endorsement of Institutional Shareholder Services (ISS) and Glass Lewis, two leading advisers to fund managers. “It brings over a lot of index funds,” says someone close to the buy-out team.Both sides believe that despite a rocky few years Dell’s prospects could be bright. Both agree that the firm must shift from selling personal computers into providing services, storage and software for companies. The metamorphosis has been under way for a while: Dell has spent $13 billion on acquisitions. But Mr Dell thinks the road ahead is so bumpy that it is best travelled under cover of private ownership. Mr Icahn...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:136:"http://www.economist.com/news/business/21581754-shareholders-may-not-michael-dells-offer-its-best-theyll-get-hobsons-choice?fsrc=rss|bus";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:123:"http://www.economist.com/news/business/21581754-shareholders-may-not-michael-dells-offer-its-best-theyll-get-hobsons-choice";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"Thu, 11 July 2013 14:58:10 GMT";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:40:"
      
      
      
      
      
    ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:49:"BP and spill settlements: Deepwater, deep pockets";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1426:"<p>A RICE mill around 40 miles (64km) north of Louisiana’s Gulf Coast received $21m. A construction firm in northern Alabama that does no business along the Gulf Coast got $9.7m. They obtained those payouts from a settlement fund set up by BP to compensate businesses harmed by the Deepwater Horizon oil spill in 2010—yet both businesses did better in that year than in previous ones.On July 8th BP argued to a federal appeals court that these awards, and many others like them, stem from a misinterpretation of the settlement’s compensation formula. It is supposed to reimburse businesses for “loss of income, earnings or profits suffered” as a result of the oil spill. To determine damage the settlement asks businesses to compare the variation in a crude measure of profit—revenue minus corresponding expenses—between three or more consecutive months from May to December 2010 (the spill began on April 20th) and a “benchmark period”, for which a claimant may choose either 2009, the average during 2008-09 or the average in 2007-09.BP says that Patrick Juneau, the claims administrator, has not kept to commonly understood definitions of revenue and expenses, and instead has allowed businesses to use self-recorded cash inflows and outflows that do not necessarily represent “revenue actually earned during that period or expenses that actually correspond with that revenue.” BP contends that...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:141:"http://www.economist.com/news/business/21581758-bp-asks-judge-apply-some-common-sense-deepwater-settlement-claims-deepwater-deep?fsrc=rss|bus";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:128:"http://www.economist.com/news/business/21581758-bp-asks-judge-apply-some-common-sense-deepwater-settlement-claims-deepwater-deep";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"Thu, 11 July 2013 14:58:10 GMT";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:40:"
      
      
      
      
      
